So i was trying to prove the following: Let $f \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow
 \mathbb{R}^m $, $g \colon \mathbb{R}^m \rightarrow
 \mathbb{R}^k $ and $h \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow
 \mathbb{R}^k $ such that $h = g \circ f$. If $f$ is differentiable  a
  t $p \in \mathbb{R}^n$ and $g$ is differentiable at $q = f(p) \in \mathbb{R}^m$ then $h$ is differentiable at $p$ and $Dh(p) = Dg(q) \circ Df(p)$ My attempt: As $f$ is differentiable at $p$ and $g$ so it is at $q$, we have \begin{align*}
f(x) &= f(p) + Df(x - p) + R_f(x),\text{ with }\frac{\Vert R_f(x)\Vert}{\Vert x-p\Vert} \rightarrow 0\text{ as } x \rightarrow p \\
g(x) &= g(q) + Dg(x - q) + R_g(x),\text{ with }\frac{\Vert R_g(x)\Vert}{\Vert x-q\Vert} \rightarrow 0\text{ as } x \rightarrow q
\end{align*}
Then, \begin{align*} h(x)&= g(f(x)) = g(f(p)) + Dg(f(x) - f(p)) + R_g(f(x))  
\\ &= g(f(p)) + Dg(Df(x-p) + R_f(x)) + R_g(f(x)) 
\\ &= (g \circ f)(p) + (Dg \circ Df)(x-p) + Dg(R_f(x)) + R_g(f(x))\end{align*} If $R(x) = Dg(R_f(x)) + R_g(f(x))$, proving $\frac{\Vert R(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} \rightarrow 0$ as $x \rightarrow p$ would be enough to complete the proof. \begin{align*}
\frac{\Vert R(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} = \frac{\Vert Dg(R_f(x)) + R_g(f(x))\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} \leq \frac{\Vert Dg(R_f(x))\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} + \frac{\Vert R_g(f(x))\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert}
\end{align*} So, i need to bound both terms. For the first one, i was thinking of $\frac{\Vert Dg(R_f(x))\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} \leq \frac{\Vert D_g\Vert \Vert R_f(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} \leq \frac{\Vert D_g + \epsilon_1 \Vert \Vert R_f(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert}$ for some $\epsilon_1 > 0$, and thus, taking $\delta_1 > 0$ such that $\frac{\Vert R_f(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} < \frac{\epsilon_2}{2(\Vert Dg + \epsilon_1\Vert)}$ if $\Vert x - p\Vert < \delta_1$ so $\frac{\Vert D_g + \epsilon_1 \Vert \Vert R_f(x)\Vert}{\Vert x - p\Vert} \leq \frac{\epsilon_2}{2}$ if $\Vert x - p \Vert < \delta_1$. Yet, i don't know how to bound the second term. Any help? Thanks in advance.
